This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with pedestrian detection using convolutional neural networks. Additionally, the use of recurrent neural networks and local competition mechanism suggests that it may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The focus on improving localization accuracy suggests that it may also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of occlusion handling, which is a common issue in computer vision and may suggest that it belongs to the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category.
